svg:text.svg:tspan: The ambiguous wording of the apparitions’ prophecies in Act 4, Scene 1 creates
uncertainty about what is true. Macbeth is told that he cannot be defeated by anyone “of
woman born”, which could mean ‘anyone’ or ‘someone who was born naturally’. Macbeth
doesn’t see this ambiguity, which makes him assume his victory is certain. In reality, the
prophecies are predicting his defeat by Macduff, who was born by Caesarean section.
This shows how the Witches use appearance to obscure reality, just as the Macbeths
do. Despite Macbeth hiding reality behind false appearances, he falls victim to a similar
deception by the Witches. This ironic twist shows that people who deceive others can be
deceived themselves, which emphasises that nothing can be trusted.
Shakespeare uses the Witches to present the distinction between appearance and
reality as blurred. In Act 1, Scene 1, the Witches chant “Fair is foul, and foul is fair”, which
implies that things which appear to be good are actually evil, and introduces the idea that
appearance may not reect reality. The metre emphasises this idea, as the stress placed
on “fair” and “foul” makes these words stand out, encouraging the audience to notice the
contrast between the two terms. However, the alliterative “f” suggests that even opposites
can appear similar, which highlights the confusion between appearance and reality.
Furthermore, Macbeth and Banquo’s reaction to the Witches in Act 1, Scene 3 emphasises
this confusion, as they ask if the Witches are “fantastical” or whether they are what they
show “outwardly”, and therefore whether they can be trusted. This shows the trust that
many characters place in appearance as a means of understanding reality.
Shakespeare also uses Macbeth’s visions to create confusion between appearance
and reality. In Macbeth’s “Is this a dagger” soliloquy, he asks a series of questions about
whether the dagger is “sensible / To feeling” or simply a “dagger of the mind”. While
he can see the dagger, he can’t touch it, which paradoxically suggests that it is both real
and imaginary. Shakespeare’s use of paradox here increases the already-established
confusion over the distinction between appearance and reality. The staging of these visions
further adds to this confusion. Banquo’s ghost usually appears on-stage, so the audience,
like Macbeth, cannot tell if it is real or imaginary. The audience’s inability to make this
distinction reinforces how easily appearance and reality may be confused.
The world of ‘Macbeth’ is one in which things aren’t as they seem. Shakespeare uses
language and visions to show how vastly different appearance can be from reality, and how
this can be used to deceive others. Throughout the play, Shakespeare creates a complex
and confusing relationship between appearance and reality that leaves the characters and
audience questioning the reliability of everything they have experienced.
